...it's a city? You stop in a old and probably abandoned subway station, with your only option in terms of moving is to go up the stairs straight ahead of you. Every other place has been blocked off by tall steel walls. It opens up to a rainy scene in the middle of the night. Buildings and skyscrapers surround you, struggling to stay talk as some of them have suffered major structural damage and clearly haven't been so much as looked at for quite a while, though the lights are still functional everywhere. The mini-park in the middle of the block you end up has overgrown grass and trees, benches that seem to be falling apart, and water fountains that no longer work, but there are also 20 podiums and a host section. There's the trial place, you guess. The stands themselves are brand new and seemingly have been polished very recently, letting them shine brightly in the rain and lights. Not a single dent has been made on them, and they even have a little voting machine embedded into them. As you stand in the stands, you get the feeling you aren't supposed to be here. The cars lining up the roads seem to face you, almost staring at you. The lampposts refuse to stay on, almost as if they were only staying on because they had to for your sake. And the rain, again, certainly isn't really helping, though it's too light to be disruptive and if anything, it's rather nice. At least it's not a desert, right?
